      <section class="sec" id="economy">
        <h2>Economic Outlook</h2>
        <h3>Colombia</h3>
        <p>Colombia's economy is in a slow-but-steady recovery. After a sharp deceleration to 0.6% in 2023, growth rebounded to 1.7% in 2024 and is projected at 2.6–2.9% for 2026. The Banco de la República has navigated inflation down from its peak, but at ~4.7% it remains above the 3% target — interest rates could reach 10% in 2026. FDI declined 15.2% between 2023-2024, though non-extractive investment grew 3.4%.</p>
        <p class="source-citation">Sources: <a href="https://www.bbvaresearch.com/en/publicaciones/colombia-economic-outlook-march-2026/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">BBVA Research</a> · <a href="https://www.oecd.org/en/publications/oecd-economic-outlook-volume-2025-issue-1_83363382-en/full-report/colombia_742ba6d2.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">OECD</a></p>

        <h3>Venezuela</h3>
        <p>Venezuela's numbers are eye-popping by comparison but carry significant caveats. CEPAL projects 6.5% growth for 2026 — the fastest in South America. The local firm Ecoanalítica forecasts 15.2%, with an average of 12% annually through 2029. But this recovery comes off a catastrophic base: GDP contracted by over 75% between 2013 and 2020. Inflation remains in triple digits (~272%), and over 70% of the population lives in poverty.</p>
        <p class="source-citation">Sources: <a href="https://en.cibercuba.com/noticias/2026-04-28-u1-e197721-s27061-nid327518-cepal-venezuela-estara-economias-creceran-sudamerica" target="_blank" rel="noopener">CEPAL/CiberCuba</a> · <a href="https://ecosistemag.com/en/what-to-expect-from-the-venezuelan-economy-in-2026-key-takeaways-from-the-ecoanalitica-forum/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Ecoanalítica</a></p>
      </section>

